temp.fibHeap.stixar.graph.attr
Interface Attributable

All Known Subinterfaces:
Edge, Node
All Known Implementing Classes:
AttributableBase, BasicEdge, BasicNode, BasicUEdge, BasicUNode
public interface Attributable

Attributable objects.

Attributable objects subscribe to a contract in which they have int identifiers which are unique and either use their attributability in an ad hoc manner, or use it via managed attributes.

Ad hoc use allows getting and setting values in arbitrary arrays (or BitSets) but requires that the attribute group to which the attributable object belongs does not change during the lifetime of the array. The attributable group is typically a set of nodes or edges in a graph. Ad hoc attribution requires one easily inlinable method call per get/set.

managed attributes are created via an AttrManager, which in turn keeps the attributable objects aligned with their attributes in the face of changes in the respective attribute groups. Managed attributes require two easily inlinable method calls per get or set.

Managed attributes allow symmetric syntax according to preference. Given an attributable object a and a managed attribute map m such as a NodeMap, one can either
  1. a.get(m), a.set(m, v)
  2. m.get(a), m.set(a, v)
However, in the case that the managed attribute map is native, such as an IntEdgeMap, the respective get and set method names for the attributable items append the native type (e.g. getInt, and setInt). The native maps do undergo this transformation but rather keep the get and set methods, which seems more intuitive for maps.
